46:30.499 --> 46:39.394
So political correctness is not a... it doesn't dominate in the same way.

46:39.830 --> 46:42.192
as it does in the United States.

46:42.212 --> 46:46.637
And you don't get the same sort of intellectual fashions which become a sort of rooted doctrine.

46:47.378 --> 46:47.518
No.

46:48.719 --> 46:51.582
It's a central chapter in this new book that I'm writing.

46:51.602 --> 46:53.083
It's very interesting.

46:53.884 --> 46:55.065
So there's no problem.

46:55.105 --> 46:59.129
There is an understanding of what the core knowledge should be.

46:59.189 --> 47:00.651
There are core knowledge.

47:00.671 --> 47:07.778
Well... I mean, as a historian, I...

47:08.922 --> 47:16.133
rather resist the idea that there is a core knowledge.

47:16.173 --> 47:30.976
But I didn't like what the Thatcher government was trying to do on my subject, which is history, which was to say that it must be very nationalist and it must push the national side.

47:31.237 --> 47:33.360
And they were expecting that we would

47:33.560 --> 47:40.789
put in place an assessment system, which in effect would have said that some facts were more important than other facts.

47:40.809 --> 47:43.253
And as a historian, I resist that.

47:43.473 --> 47:47.318
I think that's... Did that happen?

47:48.359 --> 47:58.833
To a very limited extent, but our working group refused to make such recommendations, and it became very much the centre of a political storm about it.

47:59.394 --> 48:00.495
I mean, we weren't saying...

48:00.847 --> 48:11.599
We were saying everybody should know about Shakespeare and everybody should know about Henry VIII, but we were saying they must do it in the same last steps.

48:11.979 --> 48:24.574
You know, we wanted to leave teachers with the latitude to teach within a chronological framework about 50% of the history of this country, but also the history of other cultures we thought was very important, world history.

48:25.094 --> 48:30.280
And we were told it would be absolutely scandalous for any school child to get away with doing less than that.

48:30.850 --> 48:34.794
half of their historical learning specifically about Britain.

48:35.074 --> 48:37.897
There's a very sort of Little England approach to it.

48:37.917 --> 48:42.242
Well, it sounds like a political agenda was being imposed upon the curriculum to a degree.

48:42.402 --> 48:47.007
Well, I don't know to what extent Satch has realised who was doing it.

48:47.487 --> 48:49.209
It was herself personally.

48:49.970 --> 48:53.673
She took a very close interest, although she's never had a training in history herself.

48:54.995 --> 48:58.258
But there's a very sort of simple approach that says, you know,

48:58.964 --> 49:00.947
national greatness.

49:01.849 --> 49:18.558
So I mean I would agree, I would be standardised if my children did learn from Shakespeare as part of their general education, let alone at the university if they were doing anything.

49:18.638 --> 49:24.128
But I think there's a lot of debate to be had about how far you take the concept of the core

49:24.682 --> 49:32.134
In English literature, it may be a different question from history, and I've addressed it for history.

49:32.154 --> 49:38.604
It's not just history, of course, but we don't have the purpose of her and the foreknowledge program on the university.

49:38.624 --> 49:40.647
I've looked at some of the late curricula.

49:41.428 --> 49:50.442
When we were working on the national curriculum, California and New York both come through the recommended curriculum for history, I think.

49:50.462 --> 49:52.545
It's a very different approach.

49:52.812 --> 49:56.920
there from what we adopted.

49:57.060 --> 50:08.882
A much greater sense of the great national project being unfolded through history, which is not very British.

